---
import ToolLayout from '../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
import LuxToLumensCalculator from '../components/calculators/LuxToLumensCalculator';
import FaqBlock from '../components/FaqBlock.astro';
import RelatedTools from '../components/RelatedTools.astro';
import AdSlot from '../components/AdSlot.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import { luxToLumensFaqs } from '../data/faqs';

const path = '/lux-to-lumens-calculator';
---

<ToolLayout
  title="Lux to Lumens Calculator — Convert Lux to Lumens by Area"
  description="Convert lux to lumens using room area. Use this simple calculator to estimate total lumens for offices, desks, studios, and workspaces."
  path={path}
  h1="Lux to Lumens Calculator"
  subtitle="Convert target lux and floor area into total lumens — the essential step between lighting standards and fixture shopping."
  faqSchema={luxToLumensFaqs}
>
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-main mb-6">Calculator</h2>
    <LuxToLumensCalculator client:load />
  </section>

  <AdSlot />

  <section class="prose-content">
    <h2>How this calculator works</h2>
    <p>
      Lux and lumens measure different things, and confusing them is one of the most common mistakes in
      lighting planning. <strong>Lux</strong> (lx) is illuminance: lumens per square meter falling on a
      surface. It answers “how bright is my desk or floor?” <strong>Lumens</strong> (lm) describe total
      light output from a source or group of fixtures. A 10,000 lumen panel might produce 500 lux on a
      desk directly below it and much less in a distant corner — same lumens, different lux depending on
      distance and distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
      To convert lux to lumens for planning purposes, you need the area over which you want to achieve
      that illuminance. The formula is: <strong>lumens = lux × area (m²)</strong>. If your area is in
      square feet, convert first: m² = ft² × 0.092903. Then multiply by lux. Five hundred lux over 20
      m² requires 10,000 lumens of effective output on the work plane — not necessarily 10,000 lumens
      printed on a single box, because not every lumen from a fixture reaches the target surface.
    </p>
    <p>
      Why do standards use lux? Workplace and educational guidelines specify minimum illuminance on task
      surfaces — lux — because that is what affects visual comfort and performance. Lumens describe what
      you buy on a spec sheet. The conversion bridges “my office should be 500 lux” to “I need roughly
      X lumens of installed output for this floor area,” before you account for layout efficiency.
    </p>
    <p>
      This calculator assumes uniform illuminance across the entered area. Real rooms are not uniform:
      corners are darker, windows add daylight, and ceiling height changes how light spreads. Open offices
      with indirect lighting may need more total lumens than the bare formula suggests to hit minimum lux
      at every desk. Treat the result as a baseline for budgeting and product comparison, then add
      margin for losses or use our <a href="/office-lighting-calculator">Office Lighting Calculator</a>
      for workspace-specific presets.
    </p>
    <p>
      Common search questions map directly to this math. “How many lumens is 500 lux?” always requires
      area: 500 lux over 10 m² = 5,000 lm; over 50 m² = 25,000 lm. “300 lux vs 500 lux” is a 67%
      increase in required lumens for the same room. Once you have total lumens, divide by LED efficacy
      (lm/W) in the <a href="/lumens-to-watts-calculator">Lumens to Watts Calculator</a> to estimate
      power draw.
    </p>
    <p>
      Daylight contributes lux without adding fixture lumens. In daylit spaces you may need less electric
      lighting to meet combined targets — but for worst-case evening planning, calculate on electric
      load alone. For desk-sized areas, use smaller dimensions or the
      <a href="/desk-lighting-calculator">Desk Lighting Calculator</a> for task-specific guidance.
    </p>
    <Disclaimer />

    <h2>Common conversion examples</h2>
    <p>
      The table shows total lumens required for three room sizes at 300, 500, and 750 lux. Values assume
      uniform coverage — add headroom for real-world layouts.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Area</th>
          <th>300 lux</th>
          <th>500 lux</th>
          <th>750 lux</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>10 m²</td>
          <td>3,000 lm</td>
          <td>5,000 lm</td>
          <td>7,500 lm</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>20 m²</td>
          <td>6,000 lm</td>
          <td>10,000 lm</td>
          <td>15,000 lm</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>50 m²</td>
          <td>15,000 lm</td>
          <td>25,000 lm</td>
          <td>37,500 lm</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>When to use lux vs lumens</h2>
    <p>
      Use <strong>lux</strong> when setting or checking brightness on a surface — compliance, ergonomics,
      photography exposure on a desk, or comparing “is this room bright enough?” Use <strong>lumens</strong>
      when selecting products — LED panels, tubes, and bulbs are sold by lumen output and efficacy. The
      conversion connects the two, but photometric design (spacing, mounting height, beam angle) still
      determines whether installed lumens actually deliver your target lux everywhere you need it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <FaqBlock faqs={luxToLumensFaqs} />
  <RelatedTools currentHref={path} />
</ToolLayout>
